{"pageProps":{"note":{"id":"12fa-10-dev-prod-parity","title":"Dev Prod Parity","desc":"","updated":1680549172402,"created":1680548924553,"custom":{},"fname":"tech.practice.12-factor-app.dev-prod-parity","type":"note","vault":{"fsPath":".","selfContained":true,"name":"Dendron"},"contentHash":"02805d971b55e18a0a79526ca669b651","links":[{"from":{"fname":"tech.practice.12-factor-app","id":"12-factor-app","vaultName":"Dendron"},"type":"backlink","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":5,"offset":1819},"end":{"line":31,"column":52,"offset":1866},"indent":[]},"value":"tech.practice.12-factor-app.dev-prod-parity"}],"anchors":{},"children":[],"parent":"12-factor-app","data":{}},"body":"<h1 id=\"dev-prod-parity\">Dev Prod Parity<a aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"anchor-heading icon-link\" href=\"#dev-prod-parity\"></a></h1>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Keep development, staging, and production as similar as possible.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>Gaps between development and production manifest in three areas:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>The time gap:</strong> A developer may work on code that takes days, weeks, or even months to go into production.</li>\n<li><strong>The personnel gap:</strong> Developers write code, ops engineers deploy it.</li>\n<li><strong>The tools gap:</strong> Developers may be using a stack like Nginx, SQLite, and OS X, while the production deploy uses Apache, MySQL, and Linux.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>Apps are designed for Continuous Delivery by shrinking these gaps.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Make the time gap small: a developer may write code and have it deployed hours or even just minutes later.</li>\n<li>Make the personnel gap small: developers who wrote code are closely involved in deploying it and watching its behavior in production.</li>\n<li>Make the tools gap small: keep development and production as similar as possible.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Gaps === risk</p>\n<hr>\n<strong>Backlinks</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"/blog/notes/12-factor-app\">12-Factor App<